   <text>
      <body>
         <div type="letter">
            <opener><dateline><date when="1917-02-06">Feb. 06,1917</dateline></date>
               <salute>Dear <persName key="harriet_monroe">Harriet</persName>:</salute></opener>  
         <p>Thank you very much for this proof which I am returning. There are very few corrections, as you will see.</p>
            <p>I am awfully glad to know that you will take <title key="laquer_prints" level="a">these poems.</title> I trust you won’t feel like leaving out any of them when it comes to the point, as I find they only make eight pages and your first gentleman in the <title key="poetry" level="j">February number</title> had ten. I understand, by the way, that these are to lead off the <title key="poetry" level="j">March number.</title></p>
            <p>I expect to arrive in <placeName key="chicago">Chicago</placeName> either <date when="1917-02-24">Saturday, the 24th,</date> or <date when="1917-02-25">Sunday morning the 25th,</date> depending a little upon what I am doing in <placeName key="stLouis">St. Louis.</placeName> I shall go to the <placeName key="congress_hotel">Congress Hotel</placeName> as usual, and if you will telephone me or drop me a line there and give me instructions for my talk on Sunday — that is, where I am to be and at what hour — I will duly show up.</p>
            <p>I am awfully glad to know that you are getting on so well with your guarantee fund.</p>
            <closer>Affectinately yours,</closer>
         </div>
      </body>
